/*
Scenario 2
The HR team wants to identify products that need attention.
Using the same products table, write a query to display:
product_id
product_name
brand
price
stock

Conditions
Return products that satisfy either of these conditions:
The product belongs to the Furniture category.
OR the product has less than or equal to 5 units in stock.
Additional Requirements
Exclude products whose price is less than 1500.
Sort the results by:
Stock in ascending order (lowest stock first)
Price in descending order
*/

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT
	product_id,
	product_name,
	brand,
	price,
	stock
FROM products
WHERE (category='Furniture' OR stock<=5) 
	  AND price>=1500
ORDER BY stock ASC,
		 price DESC

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

USE E_Commerce

/*Scenario

You are a Data Analyst at an electronics retail company.

The inventory manager wants to know which brands have sufficient stock available.
Write a query to display:

Brand name
Number of products under each brand
Total stock available for that brand

Only include brands that:

Have at least 2 products
Have a total stock of 20 or more

Sort the results by total stock (highest first). */

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT 
	brand,
	COUNT(*) AS [Number of Products],
	SUM(stock) AS [Total stock available]
FROM products
GROUP BY brand
HAVING COUNT(*) >= 2
	   AND SUM(stock) >= 20
ORDER BY SUM(stock) DESC

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/*Scenario

Your manager wants to identify categories where products are generally expensive.

For each category, display:

Category
Number of products
Average product price
Highest product price

Only include categories where:

Average product price is greater than ₹15,000
Highest product price is greater than ₹50,000

Sort by average price in descending order.
*/

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT
	category,
	COUNT(*) AS [No. of Products],
	AVG(price) AS [Average Price],
	MAX(price) AS [Maximuim Price]
from products
GROUP BY category
HAVING AVG(price) > 15000
       AND MAX(price) > 50000
ORDER BY AVG(price) DESC

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/*Scenario

The warehouse team wants to identify brands that require restocking.

For each brand, display:

Brand
Total number of products
Total stock
Lowest product price

Only consider products where:

Stock is greater than 0
Category is not Furniture

After grouping, display only those brands whose total stock is less than 30.

Sort by total stock ascending.
*/

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT
	brand,
	COUNT(*) AS [Total no. Products],
	SUM(stock) AS [Total Stock],
	MIN(price) AS [Lowest Price]
FROM products
WHERE stock > 0
      AND category <> 'Furniture'
GROUP BY brand
HAVING SUM(stock) < 30
ORDER BY SUM(stock) ASC

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/*Scenario

Before publishing the annual product catalog, the company wants to review categories with a diverse product range.

For each category, display:

Category
Total products
Average price
Lowest price
Highest price

Only include categories that:

Have at least 3 products
Average price is between ₹5,000 and ₹40,000
Lowest price is greater than ₹1,000

Sort by highest price descending.*/

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT
	category,
	COUNT(*) as [Total Products],
	AVG(price) AS [Average Price],
	MIN(price) AS [Lowest Price],
	MAX(price) AS [Highest Price]
FROM products
GROUP BY category
HAVING COUNT(*) >= 3
	   AND AVG(price) BETWEEN 5000 and 40000
	   AND MIN(price) > 1000
ORDER BY MAX(price) DESC

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/*Scenario

The CEO wants a summary of high-performing brands.

For each brand, display:

Brand
Total products
Total stock
Average price
Maximum price

Only include brands that satisfy all of the following:

Brand has at least 2 products
Total stock is between 10 and 100
Average price is greater than ₹10,000
Maximum price is at least ₹20,000

Sort the result by:

Average price (descending)
Brand name (ascending)*/

-----------------------------------------SQL QUERY-----------------------------------------

SELECT
	brand,
	COUNT(*) as [Total Products],
	SUM(stock) AS [Total Stock],
	AVG(price) AS [Average Price],
	MAX(price) AS [Highest Price]
FROM products
GROUP BY brand
HAVING COUNT(*) >= 2
      AND SUM(stock) BETWEEN 10 AND 100
	  AND AVG(price) >10000
	  AND MAX(price) >= 20000
ORDER BY AVG(price) DESC,
		 brand ASC

